  "solution": "Critical missing comparison: A control group of students who scored below grade level but did NOT enroll in the program. Without this, we cannot attribute the 60% improvement to the program rather than other factors.\n\nStatistical phenomenon: Regression to the mean. Students are selected for enrollment because they scored below grade level—an extreme performance. Standardized test scores contain random measurement error and natural variation. Students whose scores fell furthest below average were likely influenced by a combination of (1) true low ability and (2) random bad luck on test day. When these students retake the test the following year, the random component regresses back toward the population average, creating apparent improvement even if the program has zero effect.\n\nExample parallel: If you identify all people experiencing severe back pain on a given day and provide a treatment, many will improve simply because they were measured at their worst point. The regression to their personal baseline mimics program efficacy.\n\nConclusion: The 60% figure is misleading without a control group comparison. The district must compare improvement rates between (1) students who received the program vs. (2) similar students who did not, to isolate the actual program effect from the statistical artifact of regression to the mean."
